When the mouse leaves the window on a MonoGame Windows Project it looks like the mouse doesn't get updated (except for the scroll wheel).

It seems when you scroll up or down when the mouse is outside the window that the mouse does get updated on a MonoGame Windows Project.

This is my code for testing, i do everything in the Draw method for easy testing.

```
protected override void Draw(GameTime gameTime)
        {
            GraphicsDevice.Clear(Color.CornflowerBlue);


            MouseState state = Mouse.GetState();

            string testString = "Mouse Position: " + (new Vector2(state.X, state.Y)).ToString()
                + "\nScrollWheelValue: " + state.ScrollWheelValue.ToString();

            // Testing button presses outside the window
            if (state.MiddleButton == ButtonState.Pressed)
                this.Exit();

            spriteBatch.Begin();
            spriteBatch.DrawString(testFont, testString, Vector2.Zero, Color.White);
            spriteBatch.End();


            base.Draw(gameTime);
        }
```

I tried this code in a Xna 4.0 project and everything gets updated outside the window and the window even closes when I press the middle button on my mouse.

I also tried it on a MonoGame Windows OpenGL Project and it seems that the mouse gets updated outside the window but when I press the middle button on my mouse the window just loses focus and it doesn't close like on Xna 4.0.
On a MonoGame Windows Project the window also loses focus and doesn't close.

I hope this helps and thanks for all the great work that you guys did!

This PR first fixes MGFX to support:

```
ColorWriteEnable = true;
ColorWriteEnable = false;
ColorWriteEnable = 0;
ColorWriteEnable = 1;
```

... in addition to `All`, `None`, `Red`, `Green`, `Blue`, and `Alpha` as valid values again.

This PR also includes a rough first pass at unit test support to MGFX content processing.  A lot more to do there still, but this is at least a start and will help begin to keep us from regressing in the future.

